subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Protoconch and teleoconch I unknown. Teleoconch II short, sculptured with numerous curved striae (
Fig. 61C
), transition to teleoconch III marked by change in sculpture (
Fig. 61A
). Teleoconch III about two times length of teleoconch II, sculptured with low rounded longitudinal ribs covered by short, sinuous, longitudinal striae (
Fig. 61D
), transition to teleoconch IV marked by incised axial line (
Fig. 61A
). Teleoconch IV sculptured with rounded longitudinal ribs covered by sinuous longitudinal threads (
Fig. 61F
), transition to teleoconch V marked by suture (
Fig. 62A
). Teleoconch V sculptured with wide, rounded longitudinal ribs covered by weak, sinuous, longitudinal lines (
Fig. 61G
), transition to teleoconch VI marked by suture (
Fig. 62A
). Teleoconch VI (last growth stage) average size for genus [Tol 
2.50–2.57 mm
], tubular, rather thick, moderately and regularly arched [Larc: 
0.85 –0.96 mm
; Arc: 
0.21–0.22 mm
], subcylindrical with slight increase in diameter from posterior to aperture, semi-transparent to opaque white (
Figs. 60A
, 
61H
). Surface with longitudinal sculpture comprised of 16–20 wide, rounded, regularly spaced ribs and weak sinuous longitudinal lines (
Figs. 61
G–H). Longitudinal interspaces narrower (
Figs. 61
G–H). Posterior [Dpe: 
0.49–0.50 mm
] with thick edge, squared shoulder (
Fig. 60C
). Septum hemispherical, pronounced (
Fig. 61H
). Mucro not visible in adult stage. Aperture [Da: 
0.61–0.64 mm
] thick, with 3–5 rounded, distally spaced axial ribs (
Fig. 61H
). No varix. Lip smooth (
Fig. 60C
). Periostracum thick, textured, light brown (
Figs. 60
G–H). Operculum thin, light brown; exterior surface with 8–10 concentric rings (
Figs. 60
D–E). Conceptual reconstruction of growth stages shown in 
Fig. 62A
.
